The Virginia PACE Authority (VPA) is a nonprofit organization that provides program administration services for Virginia cities and VPA is committed to implementing a , open market program that incorporates industry best practices and promotes clean energy in the As the program administrator, VPA works with commercial businesses, property owners, contractors and local governments to facilitate the financing of energy efficiency, renewable energy and resilient projects on both new and existing View and download the Virginia PACE Authority brochure for more Mission Our mission is to educate, promote and facilitate the implementation of clean energy and resilient solutions for commercial buildings through the administration of financing Our Story In the fall of , Abacus Property Solutions, a prominent PACE consultancy, formed a working group to discuss creating an open source, model of program administration that would provide Virginia jurisdictions a choice based on their specific This working group consisted of representatives from two lenders (Petros PACE Finance, John Marshall Bank), two project developers (Johnson ControIs , Abacus Property Solutions), and two law firms (Hirschler Fleischer, Williams Mullen). Based on experience with and research on PACE Program Administration around the country, this group foresaw an alternative model based on the following core principles: Low fees to property owners Freedom of choice in selection of service providers orientation (non-profit status) This group decided in to form the Virginia PACE Authority (VPA) to be the face of this effort to provide its alternative administration model to Virginia In , VPA applied for and was designated as a (c)(3) organization and has since been awarded three jurisdictions in Virginia including Loudoun County, Fairfax County, and the City of Team Abby Johnson, LEED AP O&M Abby Johnson is Executive Director of the Virginia PACE Authority ( VPA ) and President of Abacus Property Solutions (Abacus). Over the past seven years, she has specialized in PACE financing, designing and developing programs in Florida, Texas, Illinois, Pennsylvania, and the At the policy level, she was instrumental in fixing Virginia’s flawed PACE legislation in , and in successfully advocating for adding broad resiliency and stormwater management measures to the update of the In , she also created VPA , a nonprofit organization, to administer PACE programs exclusively in Prior to specializing in , Abby worked for over years as an originator and financial underwriter of commercial real estate as well as an architect in Italy and as a building science Abby is a board member of many sustainability and housing groups including Board of Housing and Community Development, Virginia Housing Development Authority, PACE Nation, Midatlantic PACE Alliance, and Wahoos for She has a Bachelor of Architectural History from the University of Virginia and a Master’s in Business from Bocconi University in Milan, Elizabeth Beauvais Elizabeth Beauvais is a senior consultant for VPA . She is a sustainability consultant with over years’ experience in environmental and social impact assessment, stakeholder engagement, and program design, implementation and She is a bridge builder and problem solver, whose clients have included Fortune companies, global renewable energy nonprofits, and regional Her most recent work has centered on economic development opportunities through successful strategy, metrics and partnerships to utilize Opportunity Beauvais assists VPA in incorporating financing into larger economic development and impact investment Elizabeth has a Bachelor of Arts in International Relations from University of Virginia, and a Master of Arts in International Environmental Policy and Development Economics from the Fletcher School of Law and Amy Williams Amy Williams provides marketing and support for VPA . requesting the stay if they are practicing social distancing and or wearing a We all can t wait to get out there and start traveling again, and we want to continue offering our great service in a Spending on Fitness and Wellness Isn t Slowing the Obesity Epidemic Subscribe to Fitt Insider Insider About Podcast SUBSCRIBE About Podcast SUBSCRIBE Photo | Marcel Heil, Unsplash Photo | Marcel Heil, Unsplash Fitness is Booming, so is Obesity Joe Vennare 4 Min Read Between ClassPass , Peloton , Planet Fitness , and countless options, the fitness industry is booming — but Americans are more likely to be obese today than ever Fitness spending The US fitness industry is the most lucrative in the world, bringing in $32.3B in From fitness classes and footwear to tech, Americans spent $265B on physical activity in Obesity rates Presently, % (more than Americans) are By , researchers expect the number will climb to ~50%. The problem: Spending doesn’t translate to sweating — the US ranks globally when it comes to engaging in physical And even if it did, exercise alone won’t eliminate obesity . The big picture: From fitness to food and healthcare to wellness, complexity has replaced common By failing to address the underlying causes of obesity, and with incentives misaligned across the board, we seem to be moving further away from a The Great Fitness Scam Writing for Outside Magazine , Brad Stulberg points out the growing complexity at the heart of the health and fitness industry: “One reason people make things complex is so they can sell ” Instead of looking to intricate solutions, like tech or expensive equipment, Stulberg advocates for simplicity: “Move your body often, sometimes hard, every bit ” The Western Diet Health gurus make nutrition seem impossibly complex, slyly selling us their Similarly, Big Food is complicit in the Having identified the bliss point , they engineer food to be intentionally In this case, the , unsexy solution to an industrialized food system comes from Michael Pollan’s: “Eat food, not too much, mostly ” The Wellness Industrial Complex As we’ve covered at great length , wellness is a mesmerizing combination of medicine, magic, and While the pursuit of sounds promising, a lot of what passes for wellness amounts to expensive, In reality, the more you have to pay for wellness, the less likely it is to make you Sick Care Like fitness, the US spends more on healthcare than any other nation — expenditures have surpassed $3.6T or % of Here, again, spending is not positively correlated with From chronic disease to infant mortality and life expectancy to deaths, the US ranks towards the bottom when measuring actual And that’s to say nothing of key contributors to obesity like lack of sleep , burnout and stress, or mental What Works What Sells From biohacking and longevity science to wearables and smartphone apps , complicated and expensive solutions overshadow the importance of living a healthy The American consumer is encouraged to overthink it, but it’s fairly Adopting healthy lifestyle behaviors, like regular exercise, eating a wholesome diet, and not smoking can increase lifespan by Maintaining a healthy lifestyle has also been shown to reduce the chance of mortality by %. Going deeper: As the Global Wellness Institute (GWI) points out, the discrepancy between spending and outcomes in the US represents a sharp divide between the “haves and the ” According to GWI Chair and CEO Susie Ellis, brands like Peloton, SoulCycle, and CrossFit are selling “more ‘product’ to the same individuals and not introducing more people to ” A GWI report goes on to say that the US is actually discouraging participation in physical activity by failing to provide adequate sidewalks, bike lanes, youth sports programs, and inclusive exercise As a result, in the US, fitness has become a privilege, not a Reality Check To be clear, personal responsibility is part of the And individuals must prioritize their But what does it say about the broader industry that the majority of people find it more difficult than not to make healthy choices? Putting the consumer aside, then, should fitness and wellness companies be expected to deliver on the promise of better health and , or are we only accountable to a PnL and shareholder interests? While it’s easy to get lost in the echo chamber of fitness unicorns , celebrity wellness empires , amenities , and solutions , maybe it’s time we champion simplicity, affordability, increasing access, and sustainable, behavior Worst case, maybe these two paths Share Intended for entrepreneurs, investors, and executives, Fitt Insider provides with insights and analysis on an Subscribe Recommended Reading Fitt Insider Outlook : What’s Next In Fitness & Wellness in read Sober Is The New Cool: Will Wellness Overtake Alcohol? 4 in read The Connected Fitness Wars 4 in read Real Estate Gets A Wellness Makeover 4 in read The New Athleisure Playbook 5 in read Glamping, The Next Wave of Wellness 3 in read Insider Home About Contact Subscribe Home About Contact Subscribe More From Fitt Work With Us   About | Fitt Insider Subscribe to Fitt Insider Insider About Podcast SUBSCRIBE About Podcast SUBSCRIBE T
